const fs = require('fs');
const newQ = [
{"n":70,"q":"Monotremes are a sub-group of mammals that are unique because they:","o":["A. Have no mammary glands","B. Are egg-laying mammals (oviparous)","C. Give birth to very undeveloped young in a pouch","D. Have no hair or fur"],"a":"B. Are egg-laying mammals (oviparous)","e":"Monotremes (platypus, echidna) are the only mammals that lay eggs — they are oviparous like reptiles. However, they do have mammary glands and hair, confirming their mammalian identity. They represent the most primitive mammal lineage."},
{"n":71,"q":"The correct taxonomic classification of humans (Homo sapiens) in order from Domain to Species is:","o":["A. Domain Bacteria → Kingdom Animalia → Phylum Chordata → Class Mammalia","B. Domain Eukarya → Kingdom Plantae → Phylum Chordata → Class Mammalia","C. Domain Eukarya → Kingdom Animalia → Phylum Chordata → Class Mammalia → Order Primates → Family Hominidae → Genus Homo → Species sapiens","D. Domain Eukarya → Kingdom Fungi → Phylum Chordata → Class Primates"],"a":"C. Domain Eukarya → Kingdom Animalia → Phylum Chordata → Class Mammalia → Order Primates → Family Hominidae → Genus Homo → Species sapiens","e":"The full Linnaean classification of humans: Domain Eukarya (eukaryotes), Kingdom Animalia, Phylum Chordata, Class Mammalia, Order Primates, Family Hominidae, Genus Homo, Species H. sapiens."},
{"n":72,"q":"Annelida (segmented worms) are unique among invertebrates in possessing:","o":["A. An incomplete digestive system with only one opening","B. A pseudocoelom and unsegmented body","C. A true coelom, metamerism (true segmentation), and a closed circulatory system","D. Radial symmetry and stinging cells"],"a":"C. A true coelom, metamerism (true segmentation), and a closed circulatory system","e":"Annelids have three key advances over simpler worms: (1) a true coelom fully lined by mesoderm, (2) metamerism — body divided into repeating segments (rings), and (3) a closed circulatory system with blood flowing in vessels."},
{"n":73,"q":"Mollusca are characterized by having a muscular foot, soft body, and:","o":["A. Segmented body with jointed appendages","B. Pseudocoelom and complete absence of a shell","C. A mantle that may secrete a calcareous shell, and a radula (a rasping feeding organ) in most species","D. Water vascular system and pentaradial symmetry"],"a":"C. A mantle that may secrete a calcareous shell, and a radula (a rasping feeding organ) in most species","e":"Mollusks have a mantle (a fold of tissue covering the visceral mass) that secretes the shell in shelled species. The radula is a ribbon-like tooth-bearing structure used for scraping food — absent only in bivalves (clams, oysters)."},
{"n":74,"q":"The body symmetry of adult Echinodermata is:","o":["A. Asymmetrical (no symmetry)","B. Bilateral symmetry throughout life","C. Pentaradial (five-fold radial) symmetry, though larvae are bilaterally symmetrical","D. Radial symmetry with two planes only"],"a":"C. Pentaradial (five-fold radial) symmetry, though larvae are bilaterally symmetrical","e":"Adult echinoderms (starfish, sea urchins) display pentaradial symmetry — body parts arranged in multiples of five. However, echinoderm larvae are bilaterally symmetrical, suggesting evolutionary origin from bilateral ancestors."},
{"n":75,"q":"The four defining characteristics shared by ALL members of Phylum Chordata at some stage of their life are:","o":["A. Vertebral column, closed circulatory system, four-chambered heart, paired limbs","B. Exoskeleton, jointed legs, segmentation, open circulatory system","C. Notochord, dorsal hollow nerve cord, pharyngeal slits, post-anal tail","D. Bilateral symmetry, true coelom, complete digestive system, endoskeleton"],"a":"C. Notochord, dorsal hollow nerve cord, pharyngeal slits, post-anal tail","e":"All chordates — even tunicates and lancelets — share these four features at some life stage: (1) notochord, (2) dorsal hollow nerve cord, (3) pharyngeal (gill) slits, and (4) post-anal tail. In vertebrates, the notochord is replaced by the vertebral column."},
{"n":76,"q":"Cartilaginous fishes (Chondrichthyes, e.g., sharks) differ from bony fishes (Osteichthyes) in that Chondrichthyes:","o":["A. Have a bony skeleton and operculum covering their gills","B. Have a swim bladder for buoyancy","C. Have a cartilaginous skeleton, no operculum (gills exposed), placoid scales, and internal fertilization","D. Are exclusively freshwater organisms"],"a":"C. Have a cartilaginous skeleton, no operculum (gills exposed), placoid scales, and internal fertilization","e":"Chondrichthyes (sharks, rays) have: cartilaginous (not bony) skeleton, no operculum (gill slits are exposed externally), sandpaper-like placoid scales, and internal fertilization. Osteichthyes have bone, operculum, and usually a swim bladder."},
{"n":77,"q":"The three-chambered heart of amphibians consists of:","o":["A. Three ventricles and no atria","B. Two ventricles and one atrium","C. Two atria and one (incompletely divided) ventricle","D. Four equal chambers like mammals"],"a":"C. Two atria and one (incompletely divided) ventricle","e":"Amphibians have a three-chambered heart: two atria (one receiving oxygenated blood from lungs/skin, one receiving deoxygenated blood from body) and one ventricle. Some mixing of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood occurs in the single ventricle."},
{"n":78,"q":"Which of the following statements about Class Reptilia is CORRECT?","o":["A. All reptiles have a four-chambered heart","B. Reptiles are endothermic (warm-blooded)","C. Reptiles have dry, horny scales or scutes that prevent water loss and internal fertilization","D. Reptiles always undergo metamorphosis like amphibians"],"a":"C. Reptiles have dry, horny scales or scutes that prevent water loss and internal fertilization","e":"Reptiles: dry, horny scales/scutes prevent desiccation; internal fertilization; amniotic leathery eggs; ectothermic. Most have a three-chambered heart except crocodilians (four-chambered). No metamorphosis occurs."},
{"n":79,"q":"The skeletal adaptation of birds that reduces weight for flight is called:","o":["A. A thick compact bone structure","B. Absence of all skeletal bones","C. Pneumatic bones (hollow bones with internal air cavities)","D. Replacement of bones with cartilage"],"a":"C. Pneumatic bones (hollow bones with internal air cavities)","e":"Birds have pneumatic bones — hollow bones with internal struts for strength, connected to the air sac system. This dramatically reduces body weight while maintaining structural integrity, essential for the energetics of powered flight."},
{"n":80,"q":"Marsupials (e.g., kangaroos) differ from placental mammals in that:","o":["A. They lay eggs like monotremes","B. Their young are fully developed at birth","C. Their young are born at a very early (altricial) stage and complete development in a maternal pouch","D. They lack mammary glands"],"a":"C. Their young are born at a very early (altricial) stage and complete development in a maternal pouch","e":"Marsupials have a very short gestation — young are born tiny and undeveloped, crawling to the mother's pouch (marsupium) where they attach to nipples and continue development. Placental mammals have a longer gestation with a functional placenta."},
{"n":81,"q":"The excretory structures in Platyhelminthes (flatworms) are called:","o":["A. Nephridia","B. Malpighian tubules","C. Contractile vacuoles","D. Flame cells (protonephridia)"],"a":"D. Flame cells (protonephridia)","e":"Flatworms use flame cells (protonephridia) for osmoregulation and excretion. These are hollow cells with beating cilia that resemble a flickering flame, drawing waste fluid into collecting tubules that lead to excretory pores."},
{"n":82,"q":"Which phylum has two distinct body forms — the sessile polyp and the free-swimming medusa?","o":["A. Porifera","B. Platyhelminthes","C. Echinodermata","D. Cnidaria"],"a":"D. Cnidaria","e":"Cnidaria exhibit alternation between two body forms: the polyp (sessile, e.g., Hydra, sea anemones) and the medusa (free-swimming, bell-shaped, e.g., jellyfish). Some species show only one form; others alternate between both."},
{"n":83,"q":"The skeleton of sponges (Porifera) may be made of silica or calcium carbonate spicules, or alternatively of:","o":["A. Chitin fibres","B. Cellulose plates","C. Calcium phosphate","D. Spongin (a protein fibre network)"],"a":"D. Spongin (a protein fibre network)","e":"Sponges have three skeletal types: siliceous spicules (silica), calcareous spicules (calcium carbonate), or spongin — a flexible protein network. Bath sponges are harvested for their spongin skeleton after removing the living tissue."},
{"n":84,"q":"Sharks (Chondrichthyes) detect the electric fields of prey using:","o":["A. Their lateral line system only","B. Olfactory chemoreceptors in the snout","C. The tympanic membrane","D. Ampullae of Lorenzini"],"a":"D. Ampullae of Lorenzini","e":"Sharks possess ampullae of Lorenzini — electroreceptor organs in pores on the snout that detect weak electric fields generated by muscle contractions and nerve activity in prey animals. This sense is effective even when vision and smell are impaired."},
{"n":85,"q":"The keel (enlarged sternum) of birds serves as:","o":["A. A storage organ for flight energy","B. An air-containing pneumatic bone to reduce weight","C. A sensory organ for navigation","D. The attachment site for large pectoral muscles that power the wings in flight"],"a":"D. The attachment site for large pectoral muscles that power the wings in flight","e":"The keel is a deep ridge on the sternum (breastbone) that dramatically increases the surface area for attachment of the large pectoral (chest) muscles. Flightless birds (ostriches, penguins) have a reduced or absent keel because they don't use these muscles for flight."},
{"n":86,"q":"Heterodont dentition, characteristic of most mammals, refers to:","o":["A. Having no teeth (like birds)","B. Having one type of tooth throughout life","C. Replacing teeth multiple times throughout life","D. Having different types of teeth (incisors, canines, premolars, molars) each suited to different functions"],"a":"D. Having different types of teeth (incisors, canines, premolars, molars) each suited to different functions","e":"Heterodont = 'different teeth'. Mammals have four tooth types: incisors (cutting), canines (tearing/piercing), premolars and molars (grinding). This specialization allows processing of diverse foods."},
{"n":87,"q":"In Subphylum Urochordata (tunicates), the notochord is:","o":["A. Present throughout the entire life of the organism","B. Replaced by a vertebral column in adulthood","C. Absent at all life stages","D. Present only in the larval tail, then reabsorbed when the larva metamorphoses into the sessile adult"],"a":"D. Present only in the larval tail, then reabsorbed when the larva metamorphoses into the sessile adult","e":"Tunicates (sea squirts) are remarkable: the larva looks like a tadpole with a notochord in its tail. When it settles and metamorphoses into the sessile adult, the tail (and notochord) is reabsorbed. The adult retains pharyngeal slits and a tunic but has no obvious chordate features."},
{"n":88,"q":"The Jacobson's organ (vomeronasal organ), used by many reptiles to 'smell' by flicking their tongue, is a sensory structure for:","o":["A. Detecting temperature changes","B. Hearing low-frequency sounds","C. Detecting magnetic north for navigation","D. Detecting chemical signals (chemosensation) from the environment"],"a":"D. Detecting chemical signals (chemosensation) from the environment","e":"Many reptiles (especially snakes and lizards) flick their tongues to collect chemical particles, which are then transferred to the Jacobson's (vomeronasal) organ in the roof of the mouth. This provides detailed chemical information about prey, predators, and mates."},
{"n":89,"q":"Bipedal locomotion in humans (Homo sapiens) is significant because it:","o":["A. Reduces overall brain size","B. Makes swimming more efficient","C. Prevents the use of the arms for any purpose","D. Frees the forelimbs (hands) for tool use and manipulation, contributing to advanced intelligence and culture"],"a":"D. Frees the forelimbs (hands) for tool use and manipulation, contributing to advanced intelligence and culture","e":"Human bipedalism (walking on two legs) is a key adaptation: it frees the hands for carrying objects, tool-making, and complex manipulation. Combined with an opposable thumb and enlarged neocortex, it underpins human technological and cultural evolution."},
{"n":90,"q":"The nictitating membrane in frogs is a:","o":["A. A structure used for cutaneous respiration","B. A gland that secretes poison","C. A tympanic membrane for hearing","D. A transparent or translucent third eyelid that protects and moistens the eye, especially during swimming"],"a":"D. A transparent or translucent third eyelid that protects and moistens the eye, especially during swimming","e":"The nictitating membrane (third eyelid) sweeps horizontally across the frog's eye. It is transparent to semi-transparent, protecting the eye underwater while still allowing vision. It also keeps the eye moist in air — important for semi-aquatic life."},
{"n":91,"q":"In the clade-based classification of vertebrates, Amniota includes:","o":["A. All fishes and amphibians only","B. Amphibians and reptiles only","C. Fishes, amphibians, and birds","D. Reptiles (including birds) and mammals — groups whose embryo is enclosed in an amnion"],"a":"D. Reptiles (including birds) and mammals — groups whose embryo is enclosed in an amnion","e":"Amniota = tetrapods that produce an amniotic egg (or equivalent in viviparous forms). It includes two clades: Synapsida (mammals) and Sauropsida (reptiles + birds). Amphibians and fishes are NOT amniotes — they lack amniotic eggs."},
{"n":92,"q":"Air sacs in birds contribute to 'double respiration', meaning:","o":["A. Two different types of gas are exchanged simultaneously","B. Birds breathe through both lungs and skin like amphibians","C. Birds breathe twice as fast as mammals","D. Fresh air flows through the lungs in BOTH inhalation AND exhalation, providing continuous one-way airflow for maximum oxygen extraction"],"a":"D. Fresh air flows through the lungs in BOTH inhalation AND exhalation, providing continuous one-way airflow for maximum oxygen extraction","e":"Unlike mammals (tidal breathing — air goes in and out the same route), birds have air sacs anterior and posterior to the lungs. Air flows through the lungs in one direction during both inhalation and exhalation — ensuring fresh air is always in contact with gas-exchange surfaces."},
{"n":105,"q":"Platyhelminthes are best described as:","o":["A. Acoelomate, dorsoventrally flattened worms","B. Coelomate, cylindrical worms","C. Pseudocoelomate, segmented worms","D. Eucoelomate, radially symmetrical animals"],"a":"A. Acoelomate, dorsoventrally flattened worms","e":"Platyhelminthes (flatworms) are triploblastic, acoelomate (no true body cavity), and dorsoventrally flattened. Examples include Planaria (free-living), Taenia (tapeworm), and Fasciola (liver fluke)."},
{"n":106,"q":"Which of the following is an example of Cephalochordata?","o":["A. Branchiostoma (Amphioxus)","B. Ascidia","C. Petromyzon","D. Scoliodon"],"a":"A. Branchiostoma (Amphioxus)","e":"Branchiostoma (also called Amphioxus or Lancelet) is the classic example of Cephalochordata. It is a small, marine, fish-like animal that retains all four chordate features throughout life."},
{"n":107,"q":"Arthropoda is characterized by having:","o":["A. Jointed appendages and a chitinous exoskeleton","B. Tube feet and a water vascular system","C. Nematocysts and radial symmetry","D. A mantle and radula"],"a":"A. Jointed appendages and a chitinous exoskeleton","e":"The defining features of Phylum Arthropoda are segmented bodies with jointed appendages and a chitinous exoskeleton. Arthropoda is the largest animal phylum, including insects, crustaceans, arachnids, and myriapods."},
{"n":108,"q":"Freshwater fish adapt to their hypotonic environment by:","o":["A. Never drinking water and producing large amounts of dilute urine","B. Drinking large amounts of water and producing concentrated urine","C. Excreting salts through chloride cells","D. Storing water in the swim bladder"],"a":"A. Never drinking water and producing large amounts of dilute urine","e":"Freshwater fish live in a hypertonic environment relative to their surroundings — water constantly enters their body by osmosis. They adapt by never drinking water, producing large volumes of dilute urine, and actively absorbing salts through their gills."},
{"n":109,"q":"The swim bladder in bony fish primarily functions to:","o":["A. Control buoyancy at different water depths","B. Aid in digestion","C. Store oxygen for breathing air","D. Detect sound vibrations"],"a":"A. Control buoyancy at different water depths","e":"The swim bladder (gas bladder) allows bony fish to control their buoyancy. By adjusting the amount of oxygen in the bladder, fish can achieve neutral buoyancy at different depths without continuous swimming effort."},
{"n":110,"q":"Which of the following describes the body organization level of Porifera?","o":["A. Cellular level of organization","B. Tissue level","C. Organ level","D. Organ system level"],"a":"A. Cellular level of organization","e":"Sponges (Porifera) are organized at the cellular level — they have specialized cells but these are NOT organized into true tissues or organs. This makes them the simplest of all multicellular animals."},
{"n":111,"q":"In Phylum Annelida, the body is characterized by:","o":["A. Metamerism (true segmentation) and a true coelom","B. Pseudocoelom and unsegmented body","C. Acoelomate and bilateral symmetry only","D. Open circulatory system and chitinous exoskeleton"],"a":"A. Metamerism (true segmentation) and a true coelom","e":"Annelids (e.g., earthworms, leeches) are characterized by true metamerism (body segmentation), a true coelom (eucoelomate), a closed circulatory system, and setae or parapodia for locomotion."},
{"n":112,"q":"What is the function of pharyngeal slits in adult aquatic chordates?","o":["A. Respiration (functioning as gills)","B. Feeding by filter-feeding only","C. Excretion of nitrogenous waste","D. Sound production"],"a":"A. Respiration (functioning as gills)","e":"In aquatic adult chordates (like fish), pharyngeal slits function as gill slits for respiration. In terrestrial vertebrates and embryos, these structures develop into other features such as the Eustachian tubes and tonsils."},
{"n":113,"q":"The post-anal tail in vertebrates is represented in humans by which structure?","o":["A. The coccyx (tailbone)","B. The sternum","C. The sacrum","D. The pubic symphysis"],"a":"A. The coccyx (tailbone)","e":"In adult humans, the post-anal tail is vestigial and represented by the coccyx (tailbone) — a small cluster of fused vertebrae at the base of the spine. It is a remnant of our evolutionary ancestors' tails."},
{"n":114,"q":"Nematoda (roundworms) are classified as:","o":["A. Pseudocoelomate with a complete digestive system","B. Acoelomate with an incomplete digestive system","C. Eucoelomate with a true coelom","D. Diploblastic animals"],"a":"A. Pseudocoelomate with a complete digestive system","e":"Nematodes are pseudocoelomate (the body cavity is not fully lined by mesoderm) and have a complete digestive system with both a mouth and an anus. They have a tough cuticle covering and are often parasitic."},
{"n":115,"q":"Which germ layers are present in diploblastic animals such as Cnidaria?","o":["A. Ectoderm and endoderm only","B. Ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm","C. Mesoderm and endoderm only","D. Ectoderm and mesoderm only"],"a":"A. Ectoderm and endoderm only","e":"Cnidarians (jellyfish, hydra, corals) are diploblastic — meaning they develop from only two germ layers: the ectoderm (outer) and endoderm (inner). Triploblastic animals have an additional middle layer, the mesoderm."},
{"n":116,"q":"The countercurrent exchange mechanism in fish gills ensures:","o":["A. Maximum oxygen extraction from water","B. Minimum energy use during swimming","C. Efficient removal of carbon dioxide only","D. Prevention of water loss"],"a":"A. Maximum oxygen extraction from water","e":"In the gills of fish, blood flows in the opposite direction to water over the gill lamellae. This countercurrent arrangement maintains a concentration gradient along the entire length of the gill, allowing up to 80-90% of dissolved oxygen to be extracted from the water."},
{"n":117,"q":"Which of the following is found in Mollusca but absent in bivalves?","o":["A. Radula","B. Mantle","C. Shell","D. Muscular foot"],"a":"A. Radula","e":"The radula is a rasping, tongue-like feeding organ found in most molluscs (snails, octopus, squid), but it is absent in bivalves (clams, mussels, oysters), which are filter-feeders and do not need it."},
{"n":118,"q":"Flame cells in Platyhelminthes function primarily in:","o":["A. Excretion and osmoregulation","B. Digestion","C. Gas exchange","D. Reproduction"],"a":"A. Excretion and osmoregulation","e":"Flame cells (protonephridia) in flatworms are excretory cells that remove metabolic waste and regulate water balance (osmoregulation). They beat their cilia to move fluid through the excretory canals out of the body."},
{"n":119,"q":"The classification of living organisms into groups based on shared characteristics is called:","o":["A. Taxonomy","B. Ecology","C. Physiology","D. Morphology"],"a":"A. Taxonomy","e":"Taxonomy is the scientific discipline of classifying, naming, and organizing living organisms into hierarchical groups based on their shared characteristics. It was systematized by Carl Linnaeus in the 18th century."},
{"n":120,"q":"Which structure in Urochordata is present only in the larval stage?","o":["A. Notochord","B. Tunic","C. Siphon","D. Atrium"],"a":"A. Notochord","e":"In Urochordata (sea squirts/tunicates), the notochord is present only in the larval tail region, giving the larva its characteristic tadpole-like appearance. The adult form is sessile and filter-feeding, and the notochord disappears."},
{"n":121,"q":"Which kingdom includes organisms that are prokaryotic (lack a nucleus)?","o":["A. Plantae","B. Monera","C. Fungi","D. Protoctista"],"a":"B. Monera","e":"Kingdom Monera (also called Prokaryota) includes all prokaryotic organisms — bacteria and cyanobacteria (blue-green algae) — that lack a true membrane-bound nucleus. Their genetic material is a circular DNA molecule floating in the cytoplasm."},
{"n":122,"q":"Bilateral symmetry means that an organism:","o":["A. Has no definite shape","B. Can be divided into two equal halves along one plane only","C. Has multiple planes of symmetry","D. Has radial symmetry with a central axis"],"a":"B. Can be divided into two equal halves along one plane only","e":"Bilateral symmetry means the body can be divided into two equal mirror-image halves by only ONE plane (the sagittal plane). Most advanced animals (vertebrates, insects, worms) are bilaterally symmetrical, with distinct front/back and left/right sides."},
{"n":123,"q":"What is the name given to the study of the external features of an organism?","o":["A. Anatomy","B. Morphology","C. Histology","D. Cytology"],"a":"B. Morphology","e":"Morphology is the study of the form and external structure (shape, size, external features) of organisms. It is distinct from anatomy (internal structure) and physiology (function)."},
{"n":124,"q":"Cartilaginous fish (Chondrichthyes) differ from bony fish (Osteichthyes) in that they:","o":["A. Have a swim bladder","B. Lack an operculum (exposed gills)","C. Have cycloid scales","D. Excrete ammonia"],"a":"B. Lack an operculum (exposed gills)","e":"Cartilaginous fish (sharks, rays) have exposed gill slits with no operculum covering them, unlike bony fish which have a bony opercular flap. They also have placoid scales, a cartilaginous skeleton, and internal fertilization."},
{"n":125,"q":"The binomial nomenclature system uses which two levels of classification?","o":["A. Family and Order","B. Genus and Species","C. Class and Order","D. Kingdom and Phylum"],"a":"B. Genus and Species","e":"Binomial nomenclature, developed by Carl Linnaeus, names each organism using two words: the Genus name (capitalized) and the species epithet (lowercase). For example, Homo sapiens — Homo is the genus, sapiens is the species."},
{"n":126,"q":"Which of the following is the correct hierarchical order from broadest to most specific?","o":["A. Species, Genus, Family, Order, Class, Phylum, Kingdom","B. Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Genus, Species","C. Kingdom, Class, Phylum, Order, Family, Genus, Species","D. Phylum, Kingdom, Class, Order, Genus, Family, Species"],"a":"B. Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Genus, Species","e":"The correct taxonomic hierarchy from broadest to most specific is: Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species. A helpful mnemonic is 'King Philip Came Over For Good Soup'."},
{"n":127,"q":"The kingdom Fungi is characterized by:","o":["A. Photosynthetic organisms with chlorophyll","B. Heterotrophic organisms with chitinous cell walls","C. Prokaryotic cells without organelles","D. Unicellular organisms with no cell wall"],"a":"B. Heterotrophic organisms with chitinous cell walls","e":"Fungi are eukaryotic, heterotrophic (they cannot photosynthesize) organisms with cell walls made of chitin. They obtain nutrients by absorption (secreting enzymes and absorbing digested material). Examples include mushrooms, yeasts, and moulds."},
{"n":128,"q":"Sea squirts (Ascidia) belong to which subphylum of Chordata?","o":["A. Vertebrata","B. Urochordata","C. Cephalochordata","D. Hemichordata"],"a":"B. Urochordata","e":"Ascidia (sea squirts) belong to Urochordata. They are marine, sessile adults encased in a tough tunic (cellulose-like material). Their larvae are free-swimming and show all four chordate characteristics, but adults lose the notochord and nerve cord."},
{"n":129,"q":"Sponges (Porifera) obtain their food through a process called:","o":["A. Photosynthesis","B. Filter feeding using choanocytes","C. Active hunting","D. Parasitism"],"a":"B. Filter feeding using choanocytes","e":"Sponges are filter feeders. Choanocytes (collar cells) line the internal canals and beat their flagella to draw water in through tiny pores (ostia), trapping microscopic food particles (bacteria, plankton) which are then digested intracellularly."},
{"n":130,"q":"Which of the following correctly describes the body plan of Annelida?","o":["A. Unsegmented with a pseudocoelom","B. Segmented (metameric) with a true coelom","C. Radially symmetrical with no coelom","D. Dorsoventrally flattened with no coelom"],"a":"B. Segmented (metameric) with a true coelom","e":"Annelids are segmented worms with a true coelom (eucoelomate). Metamerism (serial segmentation) is their defining feature — each segment is structurally similar. They also have a closed circulatory system and a complete digestive tract."},
{"n":131,"q":"In the Five Kingdom Classification, Kingdom Protoctista includes:","o":["A. All bacteria and blue-green algae","B. Unicellular eukaryotes and some multicellular algae","C. All fungi and slime moulds","D. All multicellular plants"],"a":"B. Unicellular eukaryotes and some multicellular algae","e":"Kingdom Protoctista (Protista) includes eukaryotic organisms that do not fit neatly into other kingdoms — mainly unicellular eukaryotes like Amoeba, Paramecium, and Euglena, plus some multicellular algae like seaweeds."},
{"n":132,"q":"The exoskeleton of arthropods is composed of:","o":["A. Calcium carbonate","B. Chitin","C. Cellulose","D. Silica"],"a":"B. Chitin","e":"The exoskeleton (outer covering) of arthropods is made of chitin, a tough polysaccharide. This rigid exoskeleton provides protection and structural support but must be periodically shed (moulted/ecdysis) as the animal grows."},
{"n":133,"q":"The water vascular system is a unique feature of which phylum?","o":["A. Mollusca","B. Echinodermata","C. Arthropoda","D. Annelida"],"a":"B. Echinodermata","e":"The water vascular system is unique to Echinodermata. It is a fluid-filled canal system that powers tube feet for locomotion, feeding, and gas exchange. It operates on hydrostatic pressure."},
{"n":134,"q":"Which fish class is represented by Petromyzon (lamprey)?","o":["A. Osteichthyes","B. Agnatha","C. Chondrichthyes","D. Sarcopterygii"],"a":"B. Agnatha","e":"Petromyzon (lamprey) belongs to Class Agnatha — the jawless fishes. Agnatha are among the most primitive vertebrates, lacking jaws and paired fins. They have a cartilaginous skeleton and an eel-like body form."},
{"n":135,"q":"Marine fish adapt to their environment by:","o":["A. Producing large volumes of dilute urine","B. Drinking seawater and excreting salts through gill chloride cells","C. Never drinking water","D. Storing salt in the swim bladder"],"a":"B. Drinking seawater and excreting salts through gill chloride cells","e":"Marine fish live in hypotonic conditions — they lose water to the salty environment by osmosis. To compensate, they drink seawater constantly, excrete excess salts through specialized gill chloride cells, and produce very small amounts of concentrated urine."},
{"n":136,"q":"Which of the following is the main distinguishing feature of Kingdom Plantae?","o":["A. Heterotrophic nutrition","B. Autotrophic nutrition via photosynthesis with chlorophyll","C. Unicellular eukaryotic organization","D. Cell wall made of chitin"],"a":"B. Autotrophic nutrition via photosynthesis with chlorophyll","e":"Kingdom Plantae comprises multicellular eukaryotes that perform photosynthesis using chlorophyll. They have cell walls made of cellulose, store food as starch, and are autotrophs — producing their own food from sunlight, CO2, and water."},
{"n":137,"q":"A coelom is defined as:","o":["A. A digestive cavity with a single opening","B. A true body cavity lined by mesoderm on all sides","C. A body cavity not completely lined by mesoderm","D. A fluid-filled space within a cell"],"a":"B. A true body cavity lined by mesoderm on all sides","e":"A coelom is a true body cavity that is completely lined by mesoderm (the middle germ layer). Animals with a true coelom are called coelomates (e.g., earthworms, vertebrates). A pseudocoelom is not fully lined by mesoderm (e.g., roundworms)."},
{"n":138,"q":"The four hallmark features of Phylum Chordata include all of the following EXCEPT:","o":["A. Dorsal hollow nerve cord","B. Closed circulatory system","C. Pharyngeal slits","D. Post-anal tail"],"a":"B. Closed circulatory system","e":"The four defining characteristics of Chordata are: (1) notochord, (2) dorsal hollow nerve cord, (3) pharyngeal slits, and (4) post-anal tail. A closed circulatory system, while common in vertebrates, is NOT one of the four chordate hallmarks."},
{"n":139,"q":"Earthworms belong to which phylum?","o":["A. Nematoda","B. Annelida","C. Platyhelminthes","D. Arthropoda"],"a":"B. Annelida","e":"Earthworms (Lumbricus terrestris) belong to Phylum Annelida. They are segmented, coelomate worms with closed circulatory systems. They use setae (tiny bristles) for locomotion and play a critical role in soil aeration and decomposition."},
{"n":140,"q":"Which type of fish lacks a swim bladder and compensates for buoyancy using an oil-rich liver?","o":["A. Bony fish (Osteichthyes)","B. Cartilaginous fish (Chondrichthyes/sharks)","C. Jawless fish (Agnatha)","D. Lungfish"],"a":"B. Cartilaginous fish (Chondrichthyes/sharks)","e":"Cartilaginous fish (sharks, rays) lack a swim bladder entirely. Instead, they use their large, oil-filled liver (oil is less dense than water) combined with dynamic lift from pectoral fins angled like airplane wings, to maintain position in the water column."},
{"n":141,"q":"Triploblastic animals are those that develop from:","o":["A. One germ layer","B. Three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, endoderm)","C. Two germ layers only","D. Four germ layers"],"a":"B. Three germ layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, endoderm)","e":"Triploblastic animals develop from three embryonic germ layers: the ectoderm (outermost), mesoderm (middle), and endoderm (innermost). The mesoderm gives rise to muscles, bones, and the circulatory system. All higher animals (from flatworms to humans) are triploblastic."},
{"n":142,"q":"Which of the following is characteristic of Class Mammalia?","o":["A. Scales and ectothermy","B. Mammary glands and endothermy (warm-bloodedness)","C. Dry scaly skin and three-chambered heart","D. Feathers and hollow bones"],"a":"B. Mammary glands and endothermy (warm-bloodedness)","e":"Mammals are characterized by mammary glands (for nursing young with milk), endothermy (they maintain constant body temperature), hair or fur, and a four-chambered heart. They give birth to live young (most species are viviparous)."},
{"n":143,"q":"An organism that is 'poikilothermic' is one that:","o":["A. Maintains a constant internal body temperature","B. Has a body temperature that varies with the environment","C. Can switch between warm and cold-blooded states","D. Lives exclusively in cold environments"],"a":"B. Has a body temperature that varies with the environment","e":"Poikilothermic (ectothermic or 'cold-blooded') animals have body temperatures that fluctuate with the surrounding environment. Fish, amphibians, and reptiles are poikilothermic. Contrast this with homeothermic (warm-blooded) animals like birds and mammals."},
{"n":144,"q":"In the kingdom Animalia, which characteristic is shared by ALL animals?","o":["A. Photosynthesis","B. Heterotrophic nutrition (cannot make own food)","C. Cell walls made of cellulose","D. Asexual reproduction only"],"a":"B. Heterotrophic nutrition (cannot make own food)","e":"All animals are heterotrophs — they cannot produce their own food by photosynthesis and must consume other organisms. They are also eukaryotic, multicellular, lack cell walls, and most are motile at some stage of life."},
{"n":145,"q":"Hirudo medicinalis (the medicinal leech) belongs to which phylum?","o":["A. Nematoda","B. Annelida","C. Platyhelminthes","D. Mollusca"],"a":"B. Annelida","e":"Hirudo medicinalis (medicinal leech) belongs to Phylum Annelida, Class Hirudinea. Leeches are segmented, coelomate worms. Hirudo has historically been used in medicine for bloodletting and is still used in microsurgery to improve blood circulation."},
{"n":146,"q":"The operculum in bony fish covers and protects which structure?","o":["A. The eye","B. The brain","C. The gills","D. The swim bladder"],"a":"C. The gills","e":"The operculum is a rigid bony flap unique to bony fish that covers and protects the gill chamber. It also plays a role in respiration by pumping water over the gills through its movements, enhancing oxygen uptake."},
{"n":147,"q":"Deuterostome animals are characterized by the blastopore becoming the:","o":["A. Mouth","B. Anus","C. Liver","D. Heart"],"a":"B. Anus","e":"In deuterostomes (including chordates and echinoderms), the blastopore (first opening in the embryo) develops into the anus, and the mouth forms secondarily from a different opening. Protostomes (insects, molluscs) show the opposite pattern — the blastopore becomes the mouth."},
{"n":148,"q":"The type of scales found on sharks (cartilaginous fish) are called:","o":["A. Cycloid scales","B. Ctenoid scales","C. Placoid scales","D. Ganoid scales"],"a":"C. Placoid scales","e":"Sharks possess placoid scales (also called dermal denticles), which are tooth-like scales with a hard enamel-like outer layer. They reduce drag by creating tiny vortices in water flow. Cycloid and ctenoid scales are found in bony fish, while ganoid scales occur in primitive fish."},
{"n":149,"q":"Hydra and jellyfish belong to which phylum?","o":["A. Porifera","B. Platyhelminthes","C. Cnidaria","D. Annelida"],"a":"C. Cnidaria","e":"Hydra, jellyfish (Aurelia), corals, and sea anemones all belong to Phylum Cnidaria. They are characterized by radial symmetry, diploblastic body plan, cnidocytes (stinging cells), and a gastrovascular cavity with a single opening."},
{"n":150,"q":"Which structure in Mollusca is responsible for secreting the shell?","o":["A. Radula","B. Muscular foot","C. Mantle","D. Siphon"],"a":"C. Mantle","e":"The mantle is a specialized layer of tissue in molluscs that wraps around the visceral mass and secretes the shell (where present). It also forms the mantle cavity which houses the gills (ctenidia) in aquatic molluscs."},
{"n":151,"q":"The 'fusiform' body shape in fish refers to:","o":["A. Flattened and disc-shaped","B. Elongated and snake-like","C. Streamlined, torpedo-shaped body","D. Spherical body form"],"a":"C. Streamlined, torpedo-shaped body","e":"A fusiform (or spindle-shaped) body is streamlined and tapers at both ends — like a torpedo. This shape minimizes water resistance (drag), allowing fish like tuna and mackerel to swim at high speeds with minimal energy expenditure."},
{"n":152,"q":"In the context of fish classification, the term 'Pisces' refers to:","o":["A. Only saltwater fish","B. Only freshwater fish","C. All fish — both bony and cartilaginous","D. Only jawless fish"],"a":"C. All fish — both bony and cartilaginous","e":"In traditional classification, 'Pisces' (or Class Pisces) is an informal grouping that includes ALL fish — jawless (Agnatha), cartilaginous (Chondrichthyes), and bony (Osteichthyes). Modern taxonomy does not use Pisces as a formal taxon because it is not monophyletic."},
{"n":153,"q":"The neural crest cells in vertebrates are unique because they give rise to:","o":["A. Only muscle cells","B. Only red blood cells","C. Facial bones, teeth, and peripheral nerves","D. Liver and pancreatic cells only"],"a":"C. Facial bones, teeth, and peripheral nerves","e":"Neural crest cells are a unique vertebrate innovation — an embryonic cell population that migrates from the dorsal neural tube to give rise to diverse structures including facial bones, teeth, peripheral nerves, sensory ganglia, and pigment cells (melanocytes)."},
{"n":154,"q":"Wuchereria bancrofti (causing elephantiasis) belongs to which phylum?","o":["A. Platyhelminthes","B. Annelida","C. Nematoda","D. Arthropoda"],"a":"C. Nematoda","e":"Wuchereria bancrofti is a parasitic roundworm belonging to Phylum Nematoda. It is transmitted by mosquitoes and causes lymphatic filariasis (elephantiasis), characterized by massive swelling of the limbs due to blockage of lymphatic vessels."},
{"n":155,"q":"Which structure in fish contains neuromast organs for detecting water movement?","o":["A. Operculum","B. Swim bladder","C. Lateral line","D. Caudal fin"],"a":"C. Lateral line","e":"The lateral line is a sensory system running along the flank of fish. It contains neuromast organs — clusters of hair cells — that detect vibrations, pressure changes, and water currents. It helps fish to school, detect predators, and navigate in murky water."},
{"n":156,"q":"The kingdom Protoctista differs from Monera in that Protoctista are:","o":["A. Prokaryotic multicellular organisms","B. Autotrophic only","C. Eukaryotic (possess a true nucleus)","D. Heterotrophic prokaryotes"],"a":"C. Eukaryotic (possess a true nucleus)","e":"Kingdom Protoctista (Protista) organisms are eukaryotic — they have a true membrane-bound nucleus and membrane-bound organelles. Kingdom Monera (bacteria) are prokaryotic — lacking a true nucleus. This is a fundamental cellular distinction."},
{"n":157,"q":"A 'complete' digestive system (as found in Nematoda and Annelida) has:","o":["A. Only a mouth and no anus","B. Only an anus with no mouth","C. Both a mouth and a separate anus","D. A single opening serving as both mouth and anus"],"a":"C. Both a mouth and a separate anus","e":"A complete digestive system has two separate openings: a mouth (for food intake) and an anus (for waste elimination), allowing for one-directional food processing. An incomplete digestive system (like in flatworms and cnidarians) has only one opening."},
{"n":158,"q":"In Phylum Echinodermata, the tube feet are operated by:","o":["A. Muscle contraction alone","B. Blood pressure changes","C. The water vascular system (hydrostatic pressure)","D. The nervous system directly"],"a":"C. The water vascular system (hydrostatic pressure)","e":"Tube feet in echinoderms are hydraulic structures powered by the water vascular system — a network of fluid-filled canals. Changes in hydrostatic (water) pressure extend or retract the tube feet, enabling movement, feeding, and adhesion to surfaces."},
{"n":159,"q":"Which of the following is a characteristic of Class Reptilia?","o":["A. Moist, scaleless skin","B. Metamorphosis in life cycle","C. Dry, scaly skin and internal fertilization","D. External fertilization in water"],"a":"C. Dry, scaly skin and internal fertilization","e":"Reptiles have dry, keratinized, scaly skin that prevents water loss — an adaptation to terrestrial life. They reproduce by internal fertilization and most lay eggs on land (oviparous). They are ectothermic (cold-blooded) and have a partially or fully divided heart."},
{"n":160,"q":"The excretory organs of earthworms are called:","o":["A. Flame cells","B. Malpighian tubules","C. Nephridia","D. Kidneys"],"a":"C. Nephridia","e":"Earthworms (Annelida) excrete waste through nephridia — tubular excretory organs that filter the coelomic fluid, reabsorb useful substances, and expel nitrogenous waste (mainly urea and ammonia) to the outside through nephridiopores."},
{"n":161,"q":"Countercurrent blood flow in fish gills ensures:","o":["A. Waste removal from blood","B. Blood clotting at the gill surface","C. Maximum oxygen uptake from water","D. Nutrient absorption through the gills"],"a":"C. Maximum oxygen uptake from water","e":"The countercurrent exchange mechanism in fish gills positions blood flow and water flow in opposite directions across the gill lamellae. This maintains a favorable oxygen concentration gradient along the entire gill surface, enabling maximum oxygen extraction from the water."},
{"n":162,"q":"Which of the following is TRUE about Kingdom Monera?","o":["A. They are eukaryotic organisms","B. They include all unicellular fungi","C. They are prokaryotes lacking a true nucleus","D. They perform photosynthesis exclusively"],"a":"C. They are prokaryotes lacking a true nucleus","e":"Kingdom Monera comprises all prokaryotes — organisms that lack a true membrane-bound nucleus. Their DNA exists as a circular chromosome in the cytoplasm (nucleoid region). They include bacteria and cyanobacteria and represent the most ancient life forms on Earth."},
{"n":163,"q":"The 'myotomes' in fish are:","o":["A. Organs for buoyancy","B. Sensory organs along the lateral line","C. W-shaped muscle segments for swimming","D. Segments of the vertebral column"],"a":"C. W-shaped muscle segments for swimming","e":"Myotomes are blocks of muscle arranged in a characteristic W-shape along the flanks of fish. When they contract in sequence, they produce the undulating, side-to-side movements that propel the fish through water. They are the primary locomotor muscles."},
{"n":164,"q":"Sharks maintain buoyancy without a swim bladder by using:","o":["A. Hollow bones","B. Inflated intestines","C. A large oil-filled liver and dynamic lift from pectoral fins","D. Air-filled chambers in their body"],"a":"C. A large oil-filled liver and dynamic lift from pectoral fins","e":"Since sharks (cartilaginous fish) lack a swim bladder, they use two strategies: (1) a large, oil-filled liver (oil is less dense than water, providing lift), and (2) dynamic lift from their pectoral fins, which work like airplane wings to generate upward force as the shark swims forward."},
{"n":165,"q":"The Phylum Mollusca body plan consists of three main parts, which are:","o":["A. Head, thorax, and abdomen","B. Head, trunk, and tail","C. Head, muscular foot, and visceral mass","D. Mantle, shell, and foot only"],"a":"C. Head, muscular foot, and visceral mass","e":"The basic molluscan body plan includes three regions: (1) the head (with sensory organs and mouth), (2) the muscular foot (for locomotion), and (3) the visceral mass (containing internal organs). The mantle covers the visceral mass and may secrete a shell."},
{"n":166,"q":"Which class of vertebrates is characterized by having feathers and hollow bones?","o":["A. Mammalia","B. Reptilia","C. Aves","D. Amphibia"],"a":"C. Aves","e":"Class Aves (birds) are characterized by feathers (unique to birds), hollow bones (pneumatic bones) that reduce weight for flight, endothermy (warm-bloodedness), a four-chambered heart, and a beak/bill with no teeth in modern species."},
{"n":167,"q":"Which is the largest phylum in the animal kingdom?","o":["A. Chordata","B. Mollusca","C. Arthropoda","D. Annelida"],"a":"C. Arthropoda","e":"Phylum Arthropoda is the largest animal phylum, comprising over 80% of all known animal species. It includes insects (Class Insecta), arachnids (spiders), crustaceans (crabs, shrimp), and myriapods (centipedes). Their success is attributed to their versatile exoskeleton, jointed appendages, and adaptability."},
{"n":168,"q":"'Bilateral symmetry' is the defining body plan of which group?","o":["A. All cnidarians","B. All echinoderms","C. Most higher animals including vertebrates and insects","D. All sponges"],"a":"C. Most higher animals including vertebrates and insects","e":"Most higher (more complex) animals — including all vertebrates, insects, annelids, and molluscs — are bilaterally symmetrical. This body plan is associated with cephalization (development of a distinct head region with concentrated sense organs) and directed locomotion."},
{"n":169,"q":"The term 'deuterostome' refers to organisms in which:","o":["A. The blastopore forms the mouth","B. Development has only one opening","C. The blastopore forms the anus; mouth forms secondarily","D. All body openings form simultaneously"],"a":"C. The blastopore forms the anus; mouth forms secondarily","e":"Deuterostomes (from Greek: 'second mouth') are animals where the blastopore (first embryonic opening) becomes the anus, and the mouth forms secondarily from a new opening. This group includes Echinodermata, Chordata, and Hemichordata — indicating their shared evolutionary ancestry."},
{"n":170,"q":"Which of the following fish structures acts as the 'main propeller' for forward movement?","o":["A. Pectoral fins","B. Pelvic fins","C. Caudal fin (tail fin)","D. Dorsal fin"],"a":"C. Caudal fin (tail fin)","e":"The caudal fin (tail fin) is the primary propulsive organ in most fish, generating thrust for forward motion. Its shape varies: a forked caudal fin (e.g., tuna) indicates fast swimming ability, while a rounded caudal fin suggests slower, more maneuverable swimming."},
{"n":171,"q":"The body wall of Cnidaria is composed of how many germ layers?","o":["A. One layer only","B. Two: ectoderm and mesoderm","C. Three: ectoderm, mesoderm, endoderm","D. Two: ectoderm and endoderm"],"a":"D. Two: ectoderm and endoderm","e":"Cnidarians (jellyfish, hydra, corals) are diploblastic — their body wall is made of only two germ layers: the ectoderm (outer layer) and endoderm (inner layer). Between these layers is a jelly-like mesoglea, but it is not a true germ layer like mesoderm."},
{"n":172,"q":"The defining feature that distinguishes vertebrates from all other chordates is the possession of:","o":["A. Pharyngeal slits","B. Notochord","C. Post-anal tail","D. Vertebral column and skull"],"a":"D. Vertebral column and skull","e":"While all chordates share the four hallmark features, what uniquely distinguishes vertebrates (subphylum Vertebrata) is the development of a vertebral column (backbone) replacing the notochord, plus a cranium (skull) protecting the brain. No other chordate subphylum has these."},
{"n":173,"q":"Which of the following adaptive features allows amphibians to live both in water and on land?","o":["A. Scales covering the body","B. Internal gills throughout life","C. Hollow bones for buoyancy","D. Moist, scaleless skin for cutaneous respiration"],"a":"D. Moist, scaleless skin for cutaneous respiration","e":"Amphibians bridge aquatic and terrestrial life partly through their moist, permeable, scaleless skin, which allows gas exchange directly through the skin (cutaneous respiration). They also use lungs as adults. However, they must remain moist and typically return to water to reproduce."},
{"n":174,"q":"Ascaris lumbricoides (intestinal roundworm) belongs to which phylum?","o":["A. Annelida","B. Platyhelminthes","C. Porifera","D. Nematoda"],"a":"D. Nematoda","e":"Ascaris lumbricoides belongs to Phylum Nematoda (roundworms). It is one of the most common human intestinal parasites, with infections (ascariasis) affecting hundreds of millions worldwide. Roundworms are cylindrical, unsegmented, and pseudocoelomate."},
{"n":175,"q":"The open circulatory system found in arthropods means that:","o":["A. Blood is always in closed vessels","B. There are no blood vessels at all","C. The heart pumps blood but has no capillaries","D. Blood (haemolymph) bathes organs directly in open body cavities"],"a":"D. Blood (haemolymph) bathes organs directly in open body cavities","e":"In an open circulatory system (found in arthropods and most molluscs), blood (called haemolymph) is pumped by the heart into open body spaces (haemocoels) where it bathes the organs directly, rather than being confined in closed blood vessels throughout the body."},
{"n":176,"q":"A sea squirt (Ascidia) as an adult is best described as:","o":["A. Free-swimming and very active","B. Burrowing and blind","C. Parasitic on fish","D. Sessile and filter-feeding, encased in a tunic"],"a":"D. Sessile and filter-feeding, encased in a tunic","e":"Adult sea squirts (tunicates) are sessile (permanently attached to a substrate), filter-feeding animals covered by a tough tunic made of a cellulose-like material called tunicin. They have two siphons — an incurrent siphon draws water in, and an excurrent siphon expels water after filter-feeding."},
{"n":177,"q":"The 'rete mirabile' in physoclistous fish is used to:","o":["A. Detect electrical fields","B. Amplify sound vibrations","C. Store reproductive eggs","D. Secrete or absorb gas in the swim bladder"],"a":"D. Secrete or absorb gas in the swim bladder","e":"In physoclistous (closed) bony fish, the swim bladder is not connected to the gut. Instead, a specialized capillary network called the rete mirabile (wonderful net) secretes or reabsorbs gases (mainly oxygen) into/out of the swim bladder, allowing fine control of buoyancy."},
{"n":178,"q":"Which of the following best describes Kingdom Fungi?","o":["A. Autotrophic with chlorophyll and cellulose cell walls","B. Prokaryotic and unicellular only","C. Motile and predatory","D. Eukaryotic, heterotrophic by absorption, with chitin cell walls"],"a":"D. Eukaryotic, heterotrophic by absorption, with chitin cell walls","e":"Fungi are eukaryotic organisms with cell walls made of chitin (not cellulose). They are heterotrophic by absorption — secreting digestive enzymes into their substrate and absorbing the products. They do not perform photosynthesis. Most are multicellular (moulds, mushrooms), though yeasts are unicellular."},
{"n":179,"q":"In fish, the pectoral and pelvic fins are classified as:","o":["A. Unpaired fins","B. Dermal fins","C. Medial fins","D. Paired fins"],"a":"D. Paired fins","e":"Fish have both paired and unpaired fins. Paired fins include the pectoral fins (located near the 'chest' region) and pelvic fins (near the ventral rear). They function in steering, braking, and balance. Unpaired (median) fins include the dorsal, caudal, and anal fins."},
{"n":180,"q":"The protective 'tunic' of sea squirts (Urochordates) is made of which material?","o":["A. Chitin (like arthropod exoskeleton)","B. Calcium carbonate (like mollusc shells)","C. Keratin (like reptile scales)","D. A cellulose-like substance called tunicin"],"a":"D. A cellulose-like substance called tunicin","e":"The tunic of urochordates is a remarkably tough covering made of tunicin, a cellulose-like polysaccharide. This is notable because cellulose production is extremely rare in animals — it is primarily a plant material. The tunic protects the adult sea squirt's body."},
{"n":181,"q":"Which of the following organisms is an example of Phylum Echinodermata?","o":["A. Nereis (polychaete worm)","B. Obelia (colonial cnidarian)","C. Helix (garden snail)","D. Asterias (starfish)"],"a":"D. Asterias (starfish)","e":"Asterias (starfish/sea star) is a classic example of Phylum Echinodermata. Other echinoderms include sea urchins (Echinus), sea cucumbers (Holothuria), brittle stars, and feather stars. All are marine, deuterostomate, and show radial symmetry as adults."},
{"n":182,"q":"Carl Linnaeus is most famous in biology for developing:","o":["A. The cell theory","B. The theory of evolution","C. The theory of genetics","D. The binomial nomenclature system of classification"],"a":"D. The binomial nomenclature system of classification","e":"Carl Linnaeus (1707-1778), the Swedish naturalist, developed the binomial nomenclature system — naming each species with a two-part Latin name (genus + species). He also established the hierarchical classification system used today. He is called the 'Father of Taxonomy'."},
{"n":183,"q":"The coccyx (tailbone) in humans represents the vestigial remnant of which chordate feature?","o":["A. The notochord","B. The pharyngeal slit","C. The dorsal hollow nerve cord","D. The post-anal tail"],"a":"D. The post-anal tail","e":"The coccyx in humans is the vestigial remnant of the post-anal tail — one of the four defining chordate features. It consists of 3-5 fused caudal vertebrae and is a clear evolutionary link to our tailed vertebrate ancestors. It still serves as an attachment point for some muscles."},
{"n":184,"q":"Which of the following is TRUE about Phylum Porifera?","o":["A. They have a true coelom","B. They are diploblastic","C. They have true tissues and organs","D. They are the most primitive multicellular animals, with no true tissues"],"a":"D. They are the most primitive multicellular animals, with no true tissues","e":"Porifera (sponges) are the most primitive multicellular animals. They lack true tissues and organs, operating at the cellular level of organization. They have no nervous system, no muscles, and no true digestive system. Each cell largely functions independently."},
{"n":185,"q":"Tilapia and Clarias (catfish) are examples of which class of fish?","o":["A. Chondrichthyes","B. Agnatha","C. Sarcopterygii","D. Osteichthyes"],"a":"D. Osteichthyes","e":"Tilapia and Clarias (African catfish) are bony fish belonging to Class Osteichthyes. Osteichthyes is characterized by a bony skeleton, gill chambers covered by an operculum, scales (cycloid or ctenoid), and typically a swim bladder for buoyancy control."},
{"n":186,"q":"The term 'oviparous' refers to organisms that:","o":["A. Give birth to live young","B. Retain eggs inside the body until hatching","C. Are hermaphroditic","D. Lay eggs that develop outside the body"],"a":"D. Lay eggs that develop outside the body","e":"Oviparous organisms reproduce by laying eggs that are fertilized and develop outside the mother's body. Most fish, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and monotreme mammals are oviparous. In contrast, viviparous organisms give birth to live young (most mammals)."},
{"n":187,"q":"The 'mantle' in molluscs functions to:","o":["A. Aid in locomotion","B. Detect chemical stimuli","C. Filter food particles","D. Cover the visceral mass and secrete the shell"],"a":"D. Cover the visceral mass and secrete the shell","e":"The mantle is a fold of tissue that covers the visceral mass (body organs) of molluscs. Its primary function is to secrete the shell (in species that have one) by depositing calcium carbonate. It also encloses the mantle cavity, which houses the gills (ctenidia) in aquatic molluscs."},
{"n":188,"q":"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of Class Aves (birds)?","o":["A. Endothermy (warm-bloodedness)","B. Hollow (pneumatic) bones","C. Four-chambered heart","D. Scales covering most of the body surface"],"a":"D. Scales covering most of the body surface","e":"Birds do NOT have scales covering most of their body — instead, they have feathers, which are unique to birds. (Note: birds do have scales on their feet/legs, inherited from their reptilian ancestors.) Endothermy, hollow bones, and a four-chambered heart ARE characteristic of birds."},
{"n":189,"q":"The classification term 'Family' comes between which two levels?","o":["A. Kingdom and Phylum","B. Phylum and Class","C. Class and Order","D. Order and Genus"],"a":"D. Order and Genus","e":"In the taxonomic hierarchy, 'Family' falls between Order and Genus: Kingdom → Phylum → Class → Order → Family → Genus → Species. For example, humans belong to Order Primates, Family Hominidae, Genus Homo, species sapiens."},
{"n":190,"q":"Which vertebrate class has a three-chambered heart (two atria, one ventricle)?","o":["A. Osteichthyes (bony fish)","B. Mammalia","C. Aves (birds)","D. Amphibia and most Reptilia"],"a":"D. Amphibia and most Reptilia","e":"Amphibians and most reptiles have a three-chambered heart — two atria and one (partially divided) ventricle. Fish have two chambers (1 atrium, 1 ventricle), while birds and mammals have four chambers (2 atria, 2 ventricles), allowing complete separation of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood."},
{"n":191,"q":"The 'pharyngeal slits' in terrestrial vertebrate embryos later develop into which adult structures?","o":["A. Ribs and sternum","B. Kidney tubules","C. Swim bladder in fish","D. Eustachian tubes, tonsils, and thymus"],"a":"D. Eustachian tubes, tonsils, and thymus","e":"In terrestrial vertebrates (including humans), pharyngeal slits are present only in embryos and never become functional gill slits. Instead, they differentiate into structures including the Eustachian tubes (connecting middle ear to pharynx), tonsils, thymus, and parts of the parathyroid glands."},
{"n":192,"q":"What is the significance of the 'five kingdom classification' system proposed by Whittaker (1969)?","o":["A. It replaced binomial nomenclature entirely","B. It was the first classification of any kind","C. It only classified animals","D. It organized life into Monera, Protoctista, Fungi, Plantae, and Animalia based on cell type, nutrition, and body organization"],"a":"D. It organized life into Monera, Protoctista, Fungi, Plantae, and Animalia based on cell type, nutrition, and body organization","e":"R.H. Whittaker's 1969 Five Kingdom system organized life based on cellular organization, mode of nutrition, and complexity, going beyond the simple plant/animal division. It includes Monera (prokaryotes), Protoctista (unicellular eukaryotes), Fungi (absorptive heterotrophs), Plantae (photosynthetic), and Animalia (ingestive multicellular)."},
{"n":193,"q":"In which phylum do organisms use 'cnidocytes' (stinging cells) to capture prey?","o":["A. Porifera","B. Mollusca","C. Arthropoda","D. Cnidaria"],"a":"D. Cnidaria","e":"Cnidocytes (also called nematocytes) are specialized stinging cells found exclusively in Phylum Cnidaria (jellyfish, hydra, corals, sea anemones). When triggered, they fire a coiled, harpoon-like thread (nematocyst) that injects venom into prey or predators."},
{"n":194,"q":"Which of the following best describes the body cavity situation in Platyhelminthes (flatworms)?","o":["A. Eucoelomate — body cavity fully lined by mesoderm","B. Pseudocoelomate — body cavity not fully lined","C. Hemocoelomate — blood-filled body cavity","D. Acoelomate — no body cavity at all"],"a":"D. Acoelomate — no body cavity at all","e":"Platyhelminthes are acoelomate — they have NO body cavity (coelom) at all. The space between the gut and the body wall is filled with a spongy parenchyma (mesenchyme). This limits their body thickness, which is why they are dorsoventrally flattened to allow diffusion for gas exchange and nutrient distribution."},
{"n":195,"q":"Which kingdom includes organisms that are prokaryotic (lack a nucleus)? [Classification]","o":["A. Plantae","B. Monera","C. Fungi","D. Protoctista"],"a":"B. Monera","e":"Kingdom Monera includes all prokaryotic organisms — bacteria and cyanobacteria — that lack a true membrane-bound nucleus."},
{"n":196,"q":"Which of the following is an invertebrate deuterostome phylum?","o":["A. Mollusca","B. Arthropoda","C. Echinodermata","D. Annelida"],"a":"C. Echinodermata","e":"Among invertebrates, Echinodermata (starfish, sea urchins) are deuterostomes — their blastopore becomes the anus and the mouth forms secondarily, linking them evolutionarily to Chordata."},
{"n":197,"q":"Which of the following is the correct description of 'viviparous' reproduction?","o":["A. Eggs hatch outside the mother's body","B. Eggs are retained inside until hatching (ovoviviparity)","C. The organism reproduces asexually","D. Young develop inside the mother and are born live"],"a":"D. Young develop inside the mother and are born live","e":"Viviparous organisms give birth to live young that develop inside the mother (usually nourished via a placenta). Most placental mammals are viviparous. This is distinct from oviparous (egg-laying) and ovoviviparous (eggs retained inside but no placenta) reproduction."},
{"n":198,"q":"The 'dorsal hollow nerve cord' of chordates is in contrast to the nervous system of arthropods, which is:","o":["A. Also dorsal and hollow","B. Absent entirely","C. Ventral and solid (ventral nerve cord)","D. Located in the tail only"],"a":"C. Ventral and solid (ventral nerve cord)","e":"Arthropods (and most other invertebrates) have a ventral solid nerve cord — running along the underside of the body. Chordates uniquely have a dorsal hollow nerve cord running along the back. This fundamental difference in nervous system position is a key distinction between the two groups."},
{"n":199,"q":"Which of the following represents the correct sequence of heart chambers from most primitive to most complex vertebrates?","o":["A. 4 chambers → 3 chambers → 2 chambers","B. 2 chambers (fish) → 3 chambers (amphibians/most reptiles) → 4 chambers (birds/mammals)","C. 3 chambers → 4 chambers → 2 chambers","D. All vertebrates have the same 4-chambered heart"],"a":"B. 2 chambers (fish) → 3 chambers (amphibians/most reptiles) → 4 chambers (birds/mammals)","e":"Heart complexity increases with vertebrate evolution: Fish have 2 chambers (1 atrium + 1 ventricle), Amphibians and most reptiles have 3 chambers (2 atria + 1 ventricle — some mixing of blood occurs), and Birds + Mammals have 4 chambers (2 atria + 2 ventricles — complete separation of oxygenated and deoxygenated blood)."},
{"n":200,"q":"Which of the following statements BEST summarizes the evolutionary significance of the amniotic egg?","o":["A. It requires water for fertilization","B. It eliminated the need for internal fertilization","C. It allowed amphibians to move back to the water","D. It freed reptiles, birds, and mammals from dependence on water for reproduction, enabling full terrestrial colonization"],"a":"D. It freed reptiles, birds, and mammals from dependence on water for reproduction, enabling full terrestrial colonization","e":"The amniotic egg (with amnion, chorion, allantois, and yolk sac membranes plus a protective shell) was the key evolutionary innovation that allowed amniotes (reptiles, birds, mammals) to reproduce entirely on land. The embryo is surrounded by fluid within the amnion and nourished by the yolk, eliminating the need for an aquatic larval stage."},
];
